{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17651594","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17651594"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:25:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:25:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18473"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18473"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.02,0.03,0.92,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11202"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79793"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11202"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18473"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65101"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4900"},{"type":"tags","id":"4903"},{"type":"tags","id":"4910"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6640"},{"type":"tags","id":"6648"},{"type":"tags","id":"6649"},{"type":"tags","id":"6812"},{"type":"tags","id":"8426"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26017"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26024"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79793","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79793"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBlood circulation through the heart and body involves a specific sequence of structures to maintain separate pulmonary and systemic circuits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the correct sequence of blood flow through the cardiopulmonary system?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Right ventricle \u2192 pulmonary arteries \u2192 right atrium \u2192 left ventricle \u2192 aorta","Right atrium \u2192 pulmonary arteries \u2192 left atrium \u2192 right ventricle \u2192 aorta","Right ventricle \u2192 pulmonary veins \u2192 left atrium \u2192 left ventricle \u2192 aorta","Right atrium \u2192 right ventricle \u2192 pulmonary trunk \u2192 pulmonary arteries \u2192 lungs \u2192 pulmonary veins \u2192 left atrium","Right atrium \u2192 left atrium \u2192 right ventricle \u2192 left ventricle \u2192 aorta"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct sequence of blood flow is \u003Cstrong\u003Eright atrium \u2192 right ventricle \u2192 pulmonary trunk \u2192 pulmonary arteries \u2192 lungs \u2192 pulmonary veins \u2192 left atrium\u003C/strong\u003E. Deoxygenated blood enters the right atrium from the superior and inferior venae cavae, flows through the tricuspid valve into the right ventricle, and is pumped through the pulmonary trunk and pulmonary arteries to the lungs. After oxygenation in the lungs, blood returns via the pulmonary veins to the left atrium.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect sequences can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight ventricle \u2192 pulmonary arteries \u2192 right atrium \u2192 left ventricle \u2192 aorta\u003C/strong\u003E - Blood does not return to the right atrium after entering pulmonary circulation\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight atrium \u2192 pulmonary arteries \u2192 left atrium \u2192 right ventricle \u2192 aorta\u003C/strong\u003E - This sequence is anatomically impossible and bypasses the right ventricle\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight ventricle \u2192 pulmonary veins \u2192 left atrium \u2192 left ventricle \u2192 aorta\u003C/strong\u003E - Blood must pass through the pulmonary arteries and lungs before reaching pulmonary veins\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight atrium \u2192 left atrium \u2192 right ventricle \u2192 left ventricle \u2192 aorta\u003C/strong\u003E - Blood cannot flow directly between the atria in a normal heart\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter reaching the left atrium, blood continues through the mitral valve to the left ventricle, which pumps it into the aorta for systemic circulation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Blood flows from the right ventricle through the pulmonary trunk to the lungs for oxygenation.","Oxygenated blood returns from the lungs via pulmonary veins to the left atrium.","The left ventricle pumps oxygenated blood to the systemic circulation via the aorta."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur A. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Lippincott Williams and Wilkins; 2017."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65101"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18473"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65101"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T20:27:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T20:29:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11202"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79793"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonym